comment:
Johnny Depp dealt with a court proven abusive woman with narcissistic personality disorder (NPD). It’s like the mainstream enables and excuses bad behavior if someone has mental illness. Contemporary culture encourages selfish and toxic behaviors in women, but men (by default), are viewed with the lens of “toxicity.” 

It’s scary. A lot of men are victims of narcissistic relationships, and that is grossly under discussed in society. This problem is exacerbated in today’s culture which dismisses men’s perspectives, especially in courts of law. Narcissism is not gender specific. I learned the hard way.

My story is pretty extreme, with an “Amber Heard” type of ex. They can be dangerous and [attempt to] ruin lives and careers with their manipulations. She went through my cell phone and has been spreading misconstrued, defamatory messages in a smear campaign to my professional colleagues. In my defense, I made a public testimonial video, which includes screenshots, legal documents and anecdotal examples of narcissist abuse from the panel, as well as of public figure I hope my story can serve as a cautionary tale and as educational media. Now she has deleted her social media accounts and still harasses me from multiple numbers, attempting to entrap me. Also threatening to release my nudes and other sensitive information. GO AHEAD! 

I was helping my covert narcissist ex-girlfriend with A LOT, and spoiled her, tolerated her abuse out of understanding, so I could try to get to the source of the issue. In retrospect, having started to understand her condition, I was attempting to give her the love she never received from her own family. I led the relationship… but as we progressed, I caught myself supplicating to her every whim and desire. Bought and did what she asked for when we went out. Guess what happened? Textbook discard and betrayal. She went through my cell phone and has been spreading misconstrued, defamatory messages about me on public forums and to my professional colleagues.

Her false defamation almost cost me my career in October 2020, and $15,000. 

In 2021, for the past several months, I’m still receiving weird messages from 14 virtual phone numbers all making allegations against me, having sensitive knowledge of my relationship with her that no one else would know but her and I. It’s hard to reason with someone who also has a personality disorder and denies their own doings, even when the stories make ZERO SENSE. I’m a reasonable man who has been trying to get her to SIT DOWN and TALK, so we can RATIONALIZE the situation, and work on SOLUTIONS. I’m VERY MENTALLY STRONG, and had the audacity believing I could fix her. It’s such a shame to see her imploding and succumbing to these delusions. I still DO CARE about her. She needs help, and if she continues down this path without direction, she’ll continue to self destruct. I know her better than anyone else, and can get her help. Such a waste. 

Learn more here about the entitlement, red flags, their mirroring, false defamations, and other behaviors from my first hand extreme experience, in this video: https://youtu.be/Yq91VnNsy6M.

comment:
You can never be absolutely sure what a person's life is like at home behind closed doors. You never fully understand the family dynamic. He's been accused of abusive behavior before. She's been accused of abuse more than once as well. It's good they aren't together. 

How much of this couple's dysfunction comes out physically and how much comes out verbally and/or emotionally, we can't know. It does seem like there were significant issues. Stick to body language though. As far as her bruises go, the first ones looked like she was hit on the outside of the eye. Was this Johnny? Only they know. This could have been an accident at home or onset. Maybe she's practicing martial arts for a part. It even goes above the end of the brow. This would have nothing to do with the mark on her cheek which looked more like a blemish. The next day, just because she didn't have a full face of makeup at the lawyer's office, doesn't mean she never had a blemish. If it was a pimple or something similar, she may have covered it up.

I didn't wear makeup very often until my 30's, but I learned to cover bruises at 17. I didn't want people asking about the hand-shaped (thumb tips are darkest) bruises around my neck. So I learned about the color wheel and covered the various stages (changing colors) of the bruising with a concealer palette. Afterward, I knew how to cover blemishes like pimples before special occasions. Sometimes my only makeup was a bit of concealer over a blemish, lip gloss, and maybe eyeliner. Amber doesn't really need makeup. She may have done the same.

I love the body language and micro-expression analyses. Maybe stick to that.

comment:
The general public needs to have a Much better understanding of Cluster B personality disorders. They throw around terms like narcissist and psychopath without really understanding of what that means and when someone turns up with these disorders, people don’t take it that seriously. 
I was in a relationship very much like this. When it finally ended, I took a picture of myself. I studied this information for a good long year. Joined support groups online, read everything I could. 
I took another picture of myself a year later and the change in appearance is SHOCKING. I looked dead with lifeless eyes before. A year later, I was back to my vibrant happy self. 

Amber is DEFINITELY in this group of “people”. You can see it just by looking at him. Then you see her and listen to what she says and it screams highly dysfunctional with severe personality disorders. 
It’s bad enough to go through this in and of itself, but it’s got to be a sheer nightmare having it play out on the world stage. 
It’s worse for men because they are supposed to be stronger and always the predator. Johnny was a victim of this vampire. 
No women should NOT always be believed. She was constantly trying to get him to hurt her and he was man enough with enough self control to not fall into that trap. 
These people are a public menace and a threat to whomever their target is. 
There is no reasoning with them and there is no amount of therapy that will help them. I’ve even read that therapists say this is the worst disorder to treat. All they do is study which behavior needs to change. They mimic that and the therapist thinks they have made a breakthrough and things are improving, when in actuality they are just getting worse. 
Please correct me if I’m wrong, but I believe it is estimated that 4% of our population has this disorder.

comment:
Johnny told her not to bring the dogs into Australia.  Depp is one person who would never think his celebrity would give him the right to break the law, especially in a country that he was working in, filming in.  The Australia debacle was 100% Amber.  AMBER totally thinks that laws are for other people, doesn't care who she upsets, and even appears to revel in upsetting people. I have no problem thinking that bringing the dogs was a way of pissing him off for telling her what to do, and she should have known what it would mean for an actor to flout such a serious law.  She could have caused the film to tank if people believed Johnny was that kind of guy.

I appreciate your information, but any one who has followed Johnny's career know that he isn't the kind of person to pull that shit.  And after watching Amber Heard, sociopath and narcissist, I have no trouble thinking she didn't give a fuck, and the outrage, and legal implications were cherries on the top of her Fuck-You-Johnny, sunday.

You don't understand how someone lets themselves get to this place in their life and marriage? 

 I was married to a sociopath for 10 years. Gaslighting and pulling the wings of flies was just normal.  Tearing me down until I almost lost every shred of dignity and confidence, using me to get through school, then leaving before I got a foreclosure notice and no idea where 6 months of mortgage payments was the END.  How could I be so stupid as to get into that place in my life and marriage?  What's the proverb?  If you drop a frog into boiling water he hops back out. If you put the frog in a pot of water and slowly increase the heat he's dead before he realizes something is horribly wrong.  It does help that sociopaths seem VERY adept at choosing targets who will blame themselves, who will give them every benefit of every doubt, while , for instance, if he chose to interpret something I said in a way that angered him, in the aftermath, I ended up apologizing.  He never hit me.  I wish he had, because that would have been my descent into the boiling water, and I'd have been gone immediately.  I just spent 10 hears while he played around with my life for his amusement.

comment:
I'm not sure if I follow your interpretation of the phrase "my truth". When I hear somebody say "this is my truth," I see it more as an expression of a perspective difference. No two people will ever remember something the exact same way. Memories are often influenced by their past and how they feel at that exact moment.
For example, two of my cats will never get passed just baseline tolerating each other's existence. Jack's truth (perspective) is a combination of envy, frustration, fear of abandonment, and "why won't you play." While Sprinkles has a perspective soaked in panic, anxiety, fear, physical pain and knowing she can't defend herself (for the love of God people stop declawing cats!).
As the third party/observer it is my job to put the two truths together and pull out the facts from the middle.
